# Tools for exploiting AD

bloodhound - used to map relationships within an Active Directory, Entra, and Azure environments.

bloodyAD - Used to perform AD priv escalation 

targetedKeroberos - can perform a number of Keroberoasting attacks

gMSADumper - Reads any gMSA password blobs the user can access and parses the values.




# AD permissions

GenericAll – Full control over the object, including password and group membership changes.

GenericWrite – Can modify most attributes of an object, but not full control.

WriteSPN – Allows writing Service Principal Names, enabling Kerberoasting attacks.

ResetPassword – Lets you reset the user’s password.

AddMember – Permission to add a user to a group.

RemoveMember – Permission to remove a user from a group.

WriteDacl – Modify the object’s permissions (ACL).

WriteOwner – Change ownership of the object.

ValidatedWriteTo – Modify security-sensitive attributes like SID history or UPN.

ValidatedWriteToSamAccountName – Specifically allows changing the SAM account name safely.

ReadProperty – Read specific attributes of an object.

WriteProperty – Write specific attributes of an object.

AllExtendedRights – Perform extended actions like “Reset Password” or “Send As.”

RemoteControl – Control a computer remotely (usually for workstation or server objects).


# Tools to use against AD

crackmapexec (CME) is a post-exploitation tool used mainly for Active Directory environments.
It allows you to:
- Enumerate information (users, shares, OS versions, domain info)
- Authenticate using credentials, NTLM hashes, or Kerberos tickets
- Execute commands remotely

Supported Protocols:
--------------------
- SMB
- RDP
- WinRM
- LDAP
- MSSQL

Basic Syntax:
-------------
crackmapexec <protocol> <target(s)> [options]


use smbclient -L // <TARGET_IP> -U '<DOMAIN>\<USER>%<PASS>' to view any shares, 
their names, type of share, and any comments.

port 445 is for SMB, should always check

Port 88/tcp (Kerberos): Runs Microsoft Windows Kerberos, 
confirming the presence of an AD environment with Kerberos authentication.

Port 464/tcp (kpasswd5): Kerberos password change service, 
part of the AD authentication infrastructure.

CPE - (Common Platform Enumeration)
Clock Skew: - coudl affect Kerberos authentication if not synced. 

